Introduction $\color{blue}{	ext{Batch Normalization (BN)}}$ has been treated as one of the standard &ldquo;plug-in&rdquo; tool to deep neural networks since its first release. It is been proved to be very helpful in a tons of machine learning applications due to its several advantages as followings:
 faster training higher learning rate easier initialization more activations support deeper but simpler architecture regularization  Algorithms:
 egin{align*} &amp;{	ext { Input: Values of } x 	ext { over a mini-batch: } \mathcal{B}= {x_{1 \ldots m}}} 
ewline &amp;{	ext { Output: } {y_{i}=\mathrm{B} \mathrm{N}_{\gamma,  eta} (x_{i})}} 
ewline &amp;{\mu_{\mathcal{B}} \leftarrow  rac{1}{m} \sum_{i=1}^{m} x_{i} \qquad 	ext { // min-batch mean}} 
ewline &amp;{\sigma_{\mathcal{B}}^{2} \leftarrow  rac{1}{m} \sum_{i=1}^{m}\left(x_{i}-\mu_{\mathcal{B}}ight)^{2} \qquad 	ext { // mini-batch variance }} 
ewline &amp;{\hat{x}_{i} \leftarrow  rac{x_{i}-\mu_{\mathcal{B}}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{\mathcal{B}}^{2}+\epsilon}} \qquad 	ext { // normalize }} 
ewline &amp;{y_{i} \leftarrow \gamma \widehat{x}_{i}+ eta \equiv \mathrm{B} \mathrm{N}_{\gamma,  eta}\left(x_{i}ight) \qquad 	ext { // scale and shift }} \end{align*}
